WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.389 --> 00:00:04.180
(soft music)

2
00:00:12.321 --> 00:00:15.107
<v ->Marc Allen is the publisher of New World Library</v>

3
00:00:15.107 --> 00:00:17.011
which publishes the work of a number of authors

4
00:00:17.011 --> 00:00:18.242
I've already interviewed.

5
00:00:18.242 --> 00:00:19.972
The reason I wanted to speak with him

6
00:00:19.972 --> 00:00:22.874
is because I noticed a plaque on his office wall that said

7
00:00:22.874 --> 00:00:25.614
best business to work for in a recent poll.

8
00:00:25.614 --> 00:00:28.482
That means there has to be a conscious boss at the top

9
00:00:28.482 --> 00:00:30.513
and it turned out that Marc was the boss.

10
00:00:30.513 --> 00:00:32.417
i absolutely loved this conversation

11
00:00:32.417 --> 00:00:34.554
with a man who is wise, quirky,

12
00:00:34.554 --> 00:00:36.626
and by his own admission, lazy.

13
00:00:36.626 --> 00:00:39.594
Nonetheless, very successful in the true meaning of the word

14
00:00:39.594 --> 00:00:42.248
and I believe he has something to teach us.

15
00:00:43.669 --> 00:00:45.962
<v Voiceover>One of the reasons I'm so happy to talk to you</v>

16
00:00:45.962 --> 00:00:47.608
is because when we come in here,

17
00:00:47.608 --> 00:00:51.328
into New World Library, I noticed there's a

18
00:00:52.608 --> 00:00:54.339
little plaque at the entryway.

19
00:00:54.339 --> 00:00:55.697
It talks about how you've been voted

20
00:00:55.697 --> 00:00:58.109
best business to work for.

21
00:00:58.109 --> 00:00:59.502
And that always impresses me

22
00:00:59.502 --> 00:01:00.881
because it means you're walking your talk

23
00:01:00.881 --> 00:01:02.181
and you're doing something right

24
00:01:02.181 --> 00:01:03.688
and that's what encouraged me to want to

25
00:01:03.688 --> 00:01:07.156
read about your personal story as a publisher.

26
00:01:07.156 --> 00:01:09.711
And I've interviewed a lot of your authors.

27
00:01:09.711 --> 00:01:12.532
And why don't we take it off from the early part

28
00:01:12.532 --> 00:01:14.192
of your life where your life looked

29
00:01:14.192 --> 00:01:15.527
nothing like it did now.

30
00:01:15.527 --> 00:01:17.327
You talk about how you had the

31
00:01:17.327 --> 00:01:20.699
opposite of the Midas touch going in your life.

32
00:01:20.699 --> 00:01:21.499
<v ->Right.</v>

33
00:01:21.499 --> 00:01:22.261
(interviewer laughs)

34
00:01:22.261 --> 00:01:24.930
In my 20s, yes, I had the opposite of the Midas touch.

35
00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:26.509
Everything I touched fell apart.

36
00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:30.778
I was born with something, or very early on

37
00:01:30.778 --> 00:01:32.589
I got something that's been very good

38
00:01:32.589 --> 00:01:33.913
and served me very well.

39
00:01:33.913 --> 00:01:36.084
I knew it was important doing what I loved.

40
00:01:36.084 --> 00:01:38.986
My dad lobbied that I should go into business.

41
00:01:38.986 --> 00:01:41.796
I knew that was not what I wanted to do.

42
00:01:41.796 --> 00:01:44.289
I didn't love the idea of going into business.

43
00:01:44.289 --> 00:01:46.785
I wanted to be an actor when I was a teenager,

44
00:01:46.785 --> 00:01:47.888
and a musician.

45
00:01:47.888 --> 00:01:49.998
And I had a band and did theater,

46
00:01:49.998 --> 00:01:52.805
so I was a theater major in college

47
00:01:52.805 --> 00:01:55.742
and then joined a theater company that fell apart

48
00:01:55.742 --> 00:01:59.442
and joined another theater company that fell apart.

49
00:01:59.442 --> 00:02:02.783
And then I wandered around, I went to a Zen center

50
00:02:02.783 --> 00:02:05.079
and got kicked out for breaking the rules.

51
00:02:05.079 --> 00:02:06.655
There were so many rules.

52
00:02:06.655 --> 00:02:09.890
And I wandered around the spiritual smorgasbord

53
00:02:09.890 --> 00:02:11.708
of Berkeley we called it

54
00:02:11.708 --> 00:02:15.583
in the late 60s, early 70s, mid 70s.

55
00:02:15.583 --> 00:02:18.688
And ended up having a rock band

56
00:02:18.688 --> 00:02:20.093
and that fell apart.

57
00:02:20.093 --> 00:02:21.567
And then I turned 30.

58
00:02:21.567 --> 00:02:23.329
<v Voiceover>You had another couple jobs in there</v>

59
00:02:23.329 --> 00:02:24.429
that you didn't do well at.

60
00:02:24.429 --> 00:02:28.362
As I recall, dishwasher, busboy, got fired, too slow.

61
00:02:28.362 --> 00:02:31.032
<v ->Yes. Many short term jobs.</v>

62
00:02:31.032 --> 00:02:34.004
I lasted two days as a busboy, a dishwasher,

63
00:02:34.004 --> 00:02:35.374
because I was too slow.

64
00:02:35.374 --> 00:02:36.779
He wanted me to work so fast.

65
00:02:36.779 --> 00:02:40.341
He wanted me to dry spoons like, shoo shoo shoo,

66
00:02:40.341 --> 00:02:42.578
for minimum wage, you know.

67
00:02:42.578 --> 00:02:44.223
Except all the desserts I could eat,

68
00:02:44.223 --> 00:02:46.290
that was my perk, desserts.

69
00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:49.726
But no, I didn't last, I lasted a day as a gardener.

70
00:02:49.726 --> 00:02:52.893
I got fired as a typesetter, the one skill I had

71
00:02:52.893 --> 00:02:55.203
was typesetting I'd learned at Dharma Press,

72
00:02:55.203 --> 00:02:58.001
the Tibetan Center Press, I'd learned how to typeset.

73
00:02:58.001 --> 00:03:00.703
And so I got a job as a typesetter

74
00:03:00.703 --> 00:03:03.072
but then I got fired for not showing up on time.

75
00:03:04.602 --> 00:03:07.047
I'm not a morning person, I never was.

76
00:03:08.507 --> 00:03:10.097
I don't do mornings very well.

77
00:03:10.097 --> 00:03:12.372
I just got up for you, I probably look like I just got up,

78
00:03:12.372 --> 00:03:14.752
and it's noon, right, so.

79
00:03:15.852 --> 00:03:18.011
<v Voiceover>What's interesting, I'm hearing a theme here.</v>

80
00:03:18.011 --> 00:03:19.990
First of all you say I was blessed with knowing

81
00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:21.523
to do what I loved, but everything

82
00:03:21.523 --> 00:03:24.062
you tried to do that you loved seemed to fall apart on you.

83
00:03:24.062 --> 00:03:25.525
<v ->Right. Exactly.</v>

84
00:03:25.525 --> 00:03:28.834
So I had a very important teaching

85
00:03:28.834 --> 00:03:30.599
which has served me well over the years,

86
00:03:30.599 --> 00:03:32.398
I knew it was important to do what I loved.

87
00:03:32.398 --> 00:03:34.175
What I didn't have was how to make it work

88
00:03:34.175 --> 00:03:35.707
financially at all.

89
00:03:35.707 --> 00:03:38.575
I woke up 30 in a total state of shock

90
00:03:38.575 --> 00:03:39.806
the day I turned 30.

91
00:03:41.226 --> 00:03:42.845
Realized I wasn't a kid anymore.

92
00:03:42.845 --> 00:03:46.011
Somehow it was cool to be a poverty case in my 20s.

93
00:03:46.011 --> 00:03:50.191
But at 30, that's this voice said you are 30,

94
00:03:50.191 --> 00:03:52.409
you're not a kid anymore.

95
00:03:52.409 --> 00:03:54.789
It's time to look at your life.

96
00:03:54.789 --> 00:03:57.726
And I spent most of the day pacing back and forth.

97
00:03:57.726 --> 00:04:01.124
I had a little one room slum apartment in Oakland,

98
00:04:01.124 --> 00:04:03.133
65 bucks a month rent.

99
00:04:03.133 --> 00:04:05.339
<v Voiceover>Which you usually had a hard time</v>

100
00:04:05.339 --> 00:04:06.205
scrounging up.

101
00:04:06.205 --> 00:04:08.108
<v ->Right, scrounging, that's a word we used all the time,</v>

102
00:04:08.108 --> 00:04:10.200
scrounging, I gotta scrounge up another

103
00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:11.860
20 bucks for rent here.

104
00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:14.205
I remember thinking it was almost magical

105
00:04:14.205 --> 00:04:17.909
how every month I would just get my 65 bucks together.

106
00:04:17.909 --> 00:04:21.078
Every month, because that's what I was visualizing,

107
00:04:21.078 --> 00:04:22.947
I need 65 bucks.

108
00:04:22.947 --> 00:04:26.393
My friend Shakti Gawain, she remembers me

109
00:04:26.393 --> 00:04:28.120
sitting up in the morning saying

110
00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:31.231
how can I get a buck and a quarter together for a latte?

111
00:04:31.231 --> 00:04:35.028
And that was my visualization for the morning.

112
00:04:35.028 --> 00:04:36.827
I need a buck and a quarter.

113
00:04:36.827 --> 00:04:38.867
<v Voiceover>So you were manifesting exactly what you</v>

114
00:04:38.867 --> 00:04:40.025
wanted and needed.

115
00:04:40.025 --> 00:04:41.732
<v ->Yes, I was, I was manifesting</v>

116
00:04:41.732 --> 00:04:44.945
exactly what I wanted and needed, yes, it's true.

117
00:04:44.945 --> 00:04:48.677
And then at age 30 I decided to raise the bar a little bit.

118
00:04:48.677 --> 00:04:49.780
<v Voiceover>A little. (laughs)</v>

119
00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:51.948
I paced up and down and I remembered,

120
00:04:51.948 --> 00:04:56.046
I'd also had a disastrous back to the land experiment

121
00:04:56.046 --> 00:04:59.390
when I was about 22 that lasted six months.

122
00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:01.085
I don't know what we were doing,

123
00:05:01.085 --> 00:05:04.797
we moved up to southwest Oregon in September

124
00:05:04.797 --> 00:05:08.060
with no buildings on the land or anything.

125
00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:11.299
And winter hit and it was the coldest, wettest,

126
00:05:11.299 --> 00:05:14.062
worst winter of my life.

127
00:05:15.742 --> 00:05:17.376
We finally, I gave up on that.

128
00:05:17.376 --> 00:05:20.139
But I remember the day I turned 30

129
00:05:20.139 --> 00:05:22.717
that one night during that back to the land experiment

130
00:05:22.717 --> 00:05:24.377
we were sitting around a fire

131
00:05:24.377 --> 00:05:27.581
and this couple, we had kind of a strange couple there

132
00:05:27.581 --> 00:05:31.018
who used to teach church camp.

133
00:05:31.018 --> 00:05:32.620
They went to church camp every year,

134
00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:34.323
they were real active in their church.

135
00:05:34.323 --> 00:05:37.528
And they said, let's play this game we play at church camp.

136
00:05:37.528 --> 00:05:39.664
Let's imagine fie years have passed

137
00:05:39.664 --> 00:05:42.102
and everything has gone as well as you could imagine,

138
00:05:42.102 --> 00:05:43.925
what would your life look like?

139
00:05:43.925 --> 00:05:45.933
And we went around the circle,

140
00:05:45.933 --> 00:05:48.035
sitting around a fire outside,

141
00:05:48.035 --> 00:05:49.544
and everybody spoke.

142
00:05:49.544 --> 00:05:51.541
I don't remember a word of what I said.

143
00:05:51.541 --> 00:05:55.430
So it obviously had not impact whatsoever in my life.

144
00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:58.144
But the day I turned 30 I remembered that.

145
00:05:58.144 --> 00:06:01.709
And I thought, this is a good exercise to do,

146
00:06:01.709 --> 00:06:03.322
this is what I should do.

147
00:06:03.322 --> 00:06:05.293
But this time I took a sheet of paper

148
00:06:05.293 --> 00:06:07.928
and I wrote, Ideal Scene, at the top.

149
00:06:07.928 --> 00:06:12.166
And I dared to imagine my ideal life.

150
00:06:12.166 --> 00:06:14.426
As soon as I started doubts and fears

151
00:06:14.426 --> 00:06:15.866
just started assaulting me.

152
00:06:15.866 --> 00:06:17.456
Oh that's way too much Marc.

153
00:06:17.456 --> 00:06:19.836
You? Dreaming all these things?

154
00:06:19.836 --> 00:06:21.833
But I was amazed what spilled out,

155
00:06:21.833 --> 00:06:24.768
it was I have a successful publishing company.

156
00:06:24.768 --> 00:06:29.548
I had no money, I had no family support financially.

157
00:06:29.548 --> 00:06:31.704
I was a total poverty case.

158
00:06:31.704 --> 00:06:33.339
I'd had no interest in business,

159
00:06:33.339 --> 00:06:35.254
I knew nothing about business.

160
00:06:36.764 --> 00:06:38.583
A friend reminded me a while ago,

161
00:06:38.583 --> 00:06:41.463
he remembered me walking along a beach saying to him,

162
00:06:41.463 --> 00:06:43.285
I don't know a thing about business.

163
00:06:43.285 --> 00:06:45.050
What do banks do anyway?

164
00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:47.128
I had no idea what a bank did.

165
00:06:47.128 --> 00:06:49.160
How they could build all these big buildings

166
00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:51.331
and how they made money, I had no idea.

167
00:06:52.141 --> 00:06:54.707
And it wasn't until I decided, okay,

168
00:06:54.707 --> 00:06:56.322
I'd start a publishing company.

169
00:06:56.322 --> 00:06:58.109
<v Voiceover>Which just came out of nowhere, right?</v>

170
00:06:58.109 --> 00:06:59.388
<v ->Out of nowhere, I was amazed.</v>

171
00:06:59.388 --> 00:07:01.377
<v Voiceover>It's like, where did that even bubble up from</v>

172
00:07:01.377 --> 00:07:02.579
into your consciousness?

173
00:07:02.579 --> 00:07:04.715
<v ->Yeah, I don't know exactly.</v>

174
00:07:04.715 --> 00:07:06.210
I'd worked some at Dharma Press,

175
00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:08.288
I was at a Tibetan center in Berkeley.

176
00:07:08.288 --> 00:07:12.526
So I saw what a publishing company was.

177
00:07:12.526 --> 00:07:14.659
Otherwise I wouldn't have even known

178
00:07:14.659 --> 00:07:16.894
what it was or what they did.

179
00:07:16.894 --> 00:07:20.594
But I had this, when I dared dream my ideal

180
00:07:20.594 --> 00:07:22.562
I had this immediate picture of

181
00:07:22.562 --> 00:07:25.940
I want to write books, I'd never written a book.

182
00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:28.704
But I don't want to be in the powerless position

183
00:07:28.704 --> 00:07:30.375
of going to all these publishers saying

184
00:07:30.375 --> 00:07:32.245
please publish my book and have them say

185
00:07:32.245 --> 00:07:33.673
they want to change it and edit it.

186
00:07:33.673 --> 00:07:35.077
I didn't want that.

187
00:07:35.077 --> 00:07:37.881
I knew my dream, when I dared dream my ideal,

188
00:07:37.881 --> 00:07:40.354
was I had this company that would publish

189
00:07:40.354 --> 00:07:43.419
whatever I wrote and publish all my friends,

190
00:07:43.419 --> 00:07:47.571
and it cruised along smoothly, it was very successful.

191
00:07:47.571 --> 00:07:50.387
Of course my doubts and fears said, you?

192
00:07:50.387 --> 00:07:52.430
Look, everything you've touched has fallen apart.

193
00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:54.497
You've been a complete failure

194
00:07:54.497 --> 00:07:56.993
repeatedly at everything you've attempted.

195
00:07:56.993 --> 00:07:59.129
Those were my doubts and fears.

196
00:07:59.129 --> 00:08:03.042
But I dared dream my ideal and I wrote it down.

197
00:08:03.042 --> 00:08:06.472
And I thought it through and I even put

198
00:08:06.472 --> 00:08:09.874
what has become maybe my unique contribution to humanity,

199
00:08:09.874 --> 00:08:13.682
I put not only do I have success as a writer,

200
00:08:13.682 --> 00:08:17.513
as a musician, creating a beautiful company

201
00:08:17.513 --> 00:08:19.820
and having a big white house on a hill

202
00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:21.353
in Marin County,

203
00:08:21.353 --> 00:08:23.629
I had a little slum apartment in Oakland,

204
00:08:23.629 --> 00:08:26.763
not only do I have all that but I also have a life of ease,

205
00:08:26.763 --> 00:08:28.095
I don't work too hard.

206
00:08:28.095 --> 00:08:31.366
I love musician's hours and actor's hours.

207
00:08:31.366 --> 00:08:34.765
We never started a thing til one in the afternoon.

208
00:08:34.765 --> 00:08:37.408
And we usually were late for that so,

209
00:08:37.408 --> 00:08:40.613
1:30 or 2 you'd get going, you know.

210
00:08:40.613 --> 00:08:43.713
That works with my biorhythm for sure.

211
00:08:43.713 --> 00:08:48.238
So that's what I wanted, a life of ease and success.

212
00:08:48.238 --> 00:08:51.981
My doubts and fears said absolutely impossible.

213
00:08:51.981 --> 00:08:53.452
It's never been done, you've gotta work

214
00:08:53.452 --> 00:08:54.792
60 to 80 hours a week.

215
00:08:54.792 --> 00:08:58.366
I had these, I was assaulted by doubts and fears.

216
00:08:59.476 --> 00:09:02.601
But I paced up and down and one way I got around them,

217
00:09:02.601 --> 00:09:05.300
I remembered hearing about Buckminster Fuller.

218
00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:09.004
People had told me he used to lecture in the 60s and 70s,

219
00:09:09.004 --> 00:09:12.870
and he looked at his life as an experiment, he said.

220
00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:15.917
He decided, he said when he was in his 20s

221
00:09:15.917 --> 00:09:17.446
he came to a point where he decided

222
00:09:17.446 --> 00:09:19.835
to either commit suicide or look at his life

223
00:09:19.835 --> 00:09:21.785
as this unique experiment.

224
00:09:21.785 --> 00:09:23.689
And fortunately he chose the experiment.

225
00:09:23.689 --> 00:09:25.059
<v Voiceover>Fortunately for all of us.</v>

226
00:09:25.059 --> 00:09:25.823
<v ->For all of us.</v>

227
00:09:25.823 --> 00:09:27.930
It really helped me out, it was critical.

228
00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:29.961
Because I just grabbed hold of that word,

229
00:09:29.961 --> 00:09:33.166
and i said to my doubts and fears, let me experiment.

230
00:09:33.166 --> 00:09:36.498
Let me go for my dream but in my own lazy way.

231
00:09:36.498 --> 00:09:38.866
Meaning, I work when I feel like it,

232
00:09:38.866 --> 00:09:40.663
which is afternoons and evenings.

233
00:09:40.663 --> 00:09:43.368
I don't do mornings, I don't do Mondays.

234
00:09:43.368 --> 00:09:46.131
Mondays is a moon day, people are emotional,

235
00:09:46.131 --> 00:09:48.148
that's the worst day to start a work week.

236
00:09:48.148 --> 00:09:49.875
<v Voiceover>But did you work Saturday Sunday?</v>

237
00:09:49.875 --> 00:09:52.275
<v ->Sometimes. Never Sunday, no.</v>

238
00:09:52.275 --> 00:09:55.688
Sunday was always just rest, day of rest.

239
00:09:55.688 --> 00:09:58.324
<v Voiceover>So mostly it was a Tuesday through Friday,</v>

240
00:09:58.324 --> 00:09:59.923
maybe Saturday, sometimes.

241
00:09:59.923 --> 00:10:01.124
<v ->Tuesday through Friday, yeah.</v>

242
00:10:01.124 --> 00:10:03.057
In fact, what evolved over the years,

243
00:10:03.057 --> 00:10:05.632
I just do Tuesday through Friday afternoon.

244
00:10:05.632 --> 00:10:08.256
And Friday's even kind of a swing day

245
00:10:08.256 --> 00:10:10.299
where I sometimes take off.

246
00:10:11.099 --> 00:10:14.275
And then Saturday I often write or do something else.

247
00:10:14.275 --> 00:10:18.673
But I never do anything on Sunday

248
00:10:18.673 --> 00:10:20.341
except family stuff.

249
00:10:20.341 --> 00:10:23.209
And Monday is my day, I never have any plans.

250
00:10:23.209 --> 00:10:24.811
It's my day alone.

251
00:10:24.811 --> 00:10:26.587
It's my favorite day of the week.

252
00:10:26.587 --> 00:10:28.886
I wake up with nothing to do.

253
00:10:28.886 --> 00:10:30.651
So some days I do a lot

254
00:10:30.651 --> 00:10:32.056
when the energy's there.

255
00:10:32.056 --> 00:10:35.051
Other Mondays I just sleep all day

256
00:10:35.051 --> 00:10:38.952
